06036nam a22006735i 9781847422194DE-B159720230228123812.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230228t20092009xxk    fo  d z      eng d  a9781847422194  a(DE-B1597)646735  a(OCoLC)647917076  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxkcGB-BST 7aPOL0280002bisacsh04a352.3/6721400aChanging local governance, changing citizens /ced. by Catherine Durose, Stephen Greasley, Liz Richardson. 1aBristol : bPolicy Press, c[2009] 4c©2009  a1 online resource (256 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tList of boxes and tables -- tAcronyms -- tNotes on contributors -- tAcknowledgments -- tForeword -- tPreface -- tChanging local governance, changing citizens: introduction -- tCitizen governance: where it came from, where it’s going -- t‘Neighbourhood’: a site for policy action, governance … and empowerment? -- tUrban housing market restructuring and the recasting of neighbourhood governance and community -- tCitizen aspirations: women, ethnicity and housing -- tCan we promote cohesion through contact? Intergroup contact and the development of community cohesion -- tNew migrants, citizenship and local governance: ‘Poles’ apart? -- tCitizens of faith in governance: opportunities, rationales and challenges -- tCitizens’ reflections on behaviour change policies -- tEvery child’s voice matters? -- te-citizenship: reconstructing the public online -- tConclusion -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe relationship between citizens and local decision makers is a long standing policy pre-occupation and has often been the subject of debate by politicians across parties. Recent governments have sought to empower, activate and give responsibility to some citizens, while other groups have been abandoned or ignored. Drawing on extensive up-to-date empirical work by leading researchers in the field, Changing local governance, changing citizens aims to explain what debates about local governance mean for local people. Questions addressed include: what new demands are being made on citizens and why? Which citizens are affected and how have they responded? What difference do changing forms of local governance make to people's lives? The book explores governance and citizenship in relation to multiculturalism, economic migration, community cohesion, housing markets, neighbourhoods, faith organisations, behaviour change and e-democracy in order to establish a differentiated, contemporary view of the ways that citizens are constituted at the local level today. Changing local governance, changing citizens provides a pertinent and robustly empirical contribution to current debates amongst policy makers, academics, practitioners and local communities about how to respond to this changing policy framework. It will be of interest to post-graduate students and academic researchers in politics, public and social policy, sociology, local government and urban studies, as well as policy makers and practitioners.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 0aLocal governmentzGreat Britain. 0aPolitical participationzGreat Britain. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / General.2bisacsh1 aAskew, Rebecca, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChapman, Rachael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChurchill, Harriet, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCotterill, Sarah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDurose, Catherine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDurose, Catherine, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGoodwin, Ma